<h2>Usage</h2>
<p>Use the Easy Read format when you need to share important written information in a way that is simple, clear and easy to understand. Easy Read is especially helpful for people with low English literacy, intellectual disability, or cognitive impairments.</p>

<p>Do:</p>
<ul>
  <li>use plain language with short sentences</li>
  <li>explain one idea per sentence or paragraph</li>
  <li>include supportive images that reinforce the message</li>
  <li>ensure the content is meaningful, accurate, and respectful</li>
  <li>test with people who use Easy Read to ensure effectiveness</li>
</ul>

<h3>When to use Easy Read</h3>
<p>Use Easy Read when:</p>
<ul>
  <li>communicating essential or public-facing information that affects people's lives</li>
  <li>writing about rights, safety, or access to services</li>
  <li>engaging people with intellectual disability or cognitive impairments</li>
</ul>

<h3>When not to use</h3>
<p>Do not use Easy Read when:</p>
<ul>
  <li>you are writing internal or technical documentation</li>
  <li>the information requires complex detail that cannot be simplified without loss of meaning</li>
  <li>you are writing for audiences who do not benefit from simplified content</li>
</ul>

<h2>How this component works</h2>
<p><strong>Text and layout</strong></p>
<p>Easy Read content should follow a consistent and structured layout. Key practices include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>using a large, easy-to-read font (minimum 14pt)</li>
  <li>left-aligning all text, without justified spacing</li>
  <li>including generous spacing between lines and sections</li>
  <li>avoiding tables, dot points, or dense paragraphs</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Images</strong></p>
<p>Images are an important part of Easy Read. They must:</p>
<ul>
  <li>directly relate to and support the accompanying text</li>
  <li>appear on the left side of the page, next to the relevant sentence</li>
  <li>be simple, clear, and easy to interpret</li>
  <li>avoid decorative use that does not add meaning</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>File format</strong></p>
<p>Easy Read documents should be published as accessible PDFs and made available alongside standard versions. Ideally, label the link clearly as "Easy Read."</p>

